\details{
\subsection{Temporal Strategies Epidemiological Foundations}{

The choice of strategy should reflect the hypothesized biological mechanism:
\itemize{
\item \strong{exact}: Immediate effects (heat stroke, hemorrhagic stroke)
\item \strong{discrete_lag}: Known delayed effect (e.g., temperature 7 days before influences dengue)
\item \strong{moving_window}: Cumulative exposure without specific lag. \strong{RECOMMENDED for elderly mortality}.
\item \strong{offset_window}: Defined incubation period (e.g., temperature 14-7 days before death)
\item \strong{distributed_lag}: Distributed lag analysis (DLNM); generates exposure matrix for \code{dlnm::crossbasis()}
\item \strong{degree_days}: Thermal threshold for vector development. GDD above temperature base accumulates over window_days.
\item \strong{seasonal}: Seasonal climate patterns for ecological or long-term studies
\item \strong{threshold_exceedance}: Counts days exceeding threshold (ideal for heatwaves)
\item \strong{cold_wave_exceedance}: Counts days below threshold (ideal for cold extremes in southern regions)
\item \strong{weighted_window}: Weighted mean modeling biological decay of exposure
}
}

\subsection{Regional Climate Considerations}{

The function automatically adapts to Brazil's diverse climates:

\strong{Tropical (North, Northeast):} Mean temperature 24-28°C, recommended temp_base 20°C (human health),
heatwave threshold Tmax > 35°C, high autocorrelation.

\strong{Subtropical (Center-West, Southeast):} Mean temperature 18-26°C, recommended temp_base 18°C,
heatwave threshold Tmax > 32°C, moderate autocorrelation.

\strong{Temperate (South):} Mean temperature 12-24°C, recommended temp_base 15°C,
heatwave threshold Tmax > 30°C, \strong{coldwave threshold Tmin < 5°C} (critical),
low autocorrelation.
}

\subsection{Causal Inference & Look-Ahead Bias}{

This function uses \strong{retroactive windows} (t-W, t), never symmetric windows (t-W, t+W).
The climate of day t+7 cannot cause a health event on day t. This design prevents
look-ahead bias, a common methodological error in environmental epidemiology.
}

\subsection{Autocorrelation in Tropical Regions}{

Temperature exhibits strong autocorrelation in tropical regions (e.g., Amazon).
When using \code{discrete_lag} or \code{distributed_lag} strategies, verify multicolinearities
in epidemiological models using \code{car::vif()}. If VIF > 5, consider using DLNM
or reducing the number of lags.
}
